segments.text: That was nothing more than what we need to eat with sourdough biscuits or sourdough bread.
And so often they say they won't rise.
The main thing is with the generation today, fast, hurry up, get on the ground, get going.
And you don't rush sourdough bread.
There's no rushing to it.
And you look at it, I put that
up the second time and that's something else.
I work mine down.
I put it up and then I work it down and let it rise.
And I didn't get it worked down.
And I said, it just will get done by 12 o'clock.
Well, it's 11.56, so I missed it for a minute.
Oh, my gosh.
But I want you to come over here before the oven gets hot, and I'll show you why I mean when I tell you that you can't brush it.
Now, here's one that's at the same time, and it's sitting out here.
And I put this in here for you.
I know you do.
I know you're such a diva.
That's incredible.
They're tripled inside.
That's just to show you, to show the average person the difference.
What it means to keep it secluded from the air.
To make it right.
This thing doesn't own anything.
But I just put it in there to keep it airtight, airtight.
Away from you.
Patience, patience.
Patience.
And that's what old folks, they'd cook on the fireplace.
And they didn't cook with a blaze.
They'd cook with coals and ashes.
The modern girl today has got to have a flame.
She's got to see it rolling.
And you burn up everything you have.
And I don't think they cook it very much anymore.
Really?
I'll bet.
Well, there isn't anybody there that can cook.
I don't have any green myra, but I'll give it a blast.
You'll let them come in.
OK. What do you think about the now, though?
Well.
And the curtains are great.
That's a beautiful room.
That is.
That little diamond in that couldn't make sense.
And let me tell you, if I had my pillows to go on that other bed, it matches up too pretty well.
It is beautiful.
It's not so pretty, but that was made in 1930.
Oh, listen, I have a question about, you know, the quilts I photographed.
You have all those in a good, safe place, don't you?
Oh, heavens, somebody stole three of them, honey, before.
What?
Yeah.
Where?
Three of those quilts have been stolen long ago.
Which ones?
One was that pretty one with the purple.
You're kidding.
No, I'm not.
Well, shoot, everybody in town knew it.
My house was robbed, honey.
I was robbed of everything nearly I had.
They didn't take valuables like the canister set and that sugar bowl.
They took your quilts?
They took three quilts, honey, that I wouldn't have parted with.
Well, then I've got the only photographs of those.
That's right.
But I'm going to have those done in posters.
You better do something because I don't have them anymore.
Well, so much has happened to me this year that I didn't realize you had lost anything.
But we'll just have to do some more.
Oh, yeah, they came in.
Oh, I've got some.
That had to be somebody you knew.
Oh, sure, it was somebody that knew that I had these.
Sure, it was somebody.
But who?
That's the whole thing.
Well, honey, the man that started this house went down at the ranch.
and stole a bunch of things.
Oh, Ava, but those were going to be exhibited.
That's what I wanted to do with them.
Okay, but there's nothing.
And he was in need of money, and I'm sure he's the one who stole them.
But I've got quilt tops.
That's similar.
Okay, okay.
So we can...
Get along with that, I hope.
Well, sure.
Okay.
Because I'm going to work on trying to get the...
The Smithsonian wants the quilts eventually, if you're willing to quilt them.
And either that or I have a big surprise for you, which I really think is very important.
They've just appropriated the funding in Austin to build a multi-million dollar museum complex for history and art of the Southwest.
It's going to be in Austin, and my goal is to be ready for them.

a little okay so we've got all of your history can be a participant in this um okay well ladybird i gave lennon and ladybird a quilt when i married when they married i would like to uh photograph that if i could star quilt is it okay it's made of you know back in 37 times were so hard and i just made it to

different pieces that I had not all the same kind like I took the pleasure of pains of doing right this and the other day when she was entertaining the dignitaries from Washington this last week out in the hangar she hung it up on the wall oh how marvelous and told them where it came from wonderful
That's wonderful.
Well, let me also ask you about the school, okay?
Yeah.
If I send, you know, the school will be in my name.
Yeah.
And it will be a front for participating in quilting organization.
And as I say, there's no money involved.
It's a nonprofit organization, as you know.
We've talked about this.
And there's nothing to it.
All you do is put $25 down, which I'm going to put $25 down.
And that's it.
And the Hill Country School of Folk Art is now in existence as soon as I file the papers.
Okay?
Well, they can meet in here.
Certainly.
In this room right here.
Yes.
And I have a big, my grandmother's old kitchen safe.
Yeah.
That I have made into a bookcase.
Wow.
Where I can put everybody's files in there.
Wonderful.
And put it against the wall in there and that long thing is where I'm going to file.
Quilt pieces and quilts.
Okay, well this is good.
The school, it's nothing to it.
It's mine.
I mean, you know, it's there.
It exists.
Once the papers are filed for $25, it's all it cost me.
And then we're organized and we can let nature take its course.
We can let appreciation for preserving the folk arts take its course.
Because, as I say, this whole thing has been done as a folk art project.
There's no great wealthy person behind it.
What's behind it is...
Guts.
Guts.
That's right.
So, I'm going to have to send you a... A determination.
Determination, that's right.
I'm going to have to get a post office box.
Why don't you just use mine?
I don't get things at Gunt Mill.
Okay.
All right, I'll do that.
I'll do that.
And later we could change it.
If we ever needed to change the address, you know, we can have it amended and change the address.
So that's no problem.
Okay, why don't I just put your post office box down for the initial beginning.
And we'll get everything done.
And then it's chartered and it is in existence.
And I met with a girl, the quilting club in Austin.
Yeah.
You know, those people will be interested in doing this.
Well, I'm not a good hand to teach quilting.
I do a lot of it.
Yeah, but we can all teach each other too.
That's the main thing.
Everybody will have to do his own deal.
Only thing is I can't stand them going down this way and pulling the thing up and doing this way.
Oh, really?
Now, if they can't get that needle and get going like that.
Oh, yeah.
That's what Mama taught me.
Oh, I can do anything.
I can't stand that down, straight, up, down, up.
That's not sewing.
You have to learn how to inch that little needle through those stitches so that you've got it even.
Yes, ma'am.
Yeah.
Yes, ma'am.
I bet you Mama put a needle and thread in my hand when I was three years old.
She said, here.
You do this way.
That's probably right.
Yeah, she did.
And I was making my own doll clothes.
I can't say they look like much, but I was doing that by the time I was gosh.
So I know what you mean about sewing right.
So we've got that going.
And then we'll get you an exhibit.
I've got my top.
Only thing I have is tops.
Well, that's okay.
We'll get those.
We'll get the tops.
We'll get that exhibited.
I mean, for his quilting.
One of them I haven't put together yet.
I'm going to put together.
Well, I started one myself.
I want to get it ready for the fall.
It's finished, but I mean, I have to set it together.
I understand, yeah.
And that's all.
I pieced each block as one along.
Did you?
Oh!
And then I put it together.
My goodness.
And when I go to put it together, then what will make the lining hold
Where you put your strips together, you quilt that.
Yes.
See, and that holds the lining straight, you see, and holds everything down.
Wonderful.
That's a different wrinkle to what anyone else has ever tried to do.
They have different ways of putting them together.
But I know how they wrinkle, and you've got seams, and you don't have any seams in your linings.
Underneath only the one middle seam where it's put together.
Well, I'll be.
I'll be if I have to.
It's a lot easier.
Well, I don't know if it's a lot easier.
But it makes a prettier finished product.
Yes, yes.
And that's what we're looking for.
That's what you're right, that craftsmanship.
That's the thing that you have down that a lot of people have.
I know we stopped at a sale on the way up from, we saw some quilts and I just stopped to look at them.
They were done on a machine.
And you simply cannot have the craftsmanship that goes into quilting by...
I don't think so.
No, it's a body touch art.
Quilting should be in so many ways.
You saw the Irish Path.
No, what was it?
Or the Dunkard's Path.
It was red set together with yellow.
Yes.
For a king-sized bed.
Right, for David.
David, uh-huh.
I have that, and I have the pillow.
Now I want to tell you, I'll put that one up against Mr.
Anybody's for being perfect in squares.
Oh, it is perfect.
I know.
I graduated in, you know, that just absolutely perfect.
It was really good, but I don't know what the rest of it will look like.
Well, I started one, too, like I say, so we'll see how it goes.
Oh, it smells great.
That's a beautiful cow.
Look how fat.
Yeah, fat's not beautiful anymore, I guess.
It might be beautiful.
Sure is comfortable, though.
Sure is comfortable.
You can sit.
You can sit down.
You can have a pretty good patty.
Yeah.
Well, that food's going to be, bread's going to be ready pretty soon, and you can have the.
Wonderful.
Have a meal.
Good.
I'm going to have to get busy going.
Uh-huh.
And sliced tomatoes.
You are, okay.
And we'll talk about that.
Yes.
So this is wonderful.
Well, all this good history is now ready to be put down.
I have to tell me another story.
I love what you're telling me about the Culter for Cattle Company.
Well, you can check on that at the university, but I'm sure that it's there.
Because I had to write a paper back in the 60s.
Uh-huh.
And I found it in the San Antonio Library.
You did.
And that's where I got it.
And I'm pretty sure that Austin University has... Oh, I'm sure that, of course, they have everything.
They have everything, and they'll probably have that.
You know, Austin, the flood really wiped everything out.
It really did mess things up.
Didn't it?
It was amazing.
I thought about you.
And...
Not because it's me, but if old Linden was living, let me tell you, Austin would have gotten some help.
No, they wouldn't.
They would have gotten a PDQ.
Right.
Yeah.
Now I'm afraid we lost our influence in Washington.
Well, I'm going to tell you right now, this fellow asked me to describe Linden.
in five sentences to a person from outer space that had never seen a man and never knew him, what could I tell, describe him?
How would I describe him?
How would you do it?
And I said, sir, do you expect me to make an atomic bomb within the next five minutes?
I said he was a dynamic person.
Energetic, vivacious, and persuasive.
Definitely persuasive.
And I want you to know he was a driver to work for.
He never quit.
But he didn't have a sister that built anything like him or a brother.
He was the only one in that family that had any drive.
That's an interesting thing that you have that drive too.
That's right.
But look at my brother and sister.
Yes.
Is it that there's only one out of the litter?
Out of the group.
There's just a constant hammer and push all the time.
I'm that way.
Push, push, push.
Keep going.
You can.
You will.
You must.
Right.
You cannot stop.
You just can't stop.
You've got to keep on.
Yes.
The elevator to success never runs.
You have to take the stair a step at a time and a day at a time.
It's hard, but that's the way it goes.
And the only reason that Lennon made the success and was the millionaire, he was at the right place at the right time and knew the right people.
That helps.
That's exactly it.
That's all of it.
That's all of it, yeah.
He got the breaks.
It wasn't that I didn't work just as hard.
But those things didn't cross my path.
Mm-hmm.
That opportunity never crossed my path.
And she did a very remarkable thing with your own life, Eva, which I respect very highly.
Well.
It held, in a certain respect, I would think it was held to your being a woman, and you were a mother, and you were married, which in fact was a tie for you to responsibility.
It was a great responsibility.
And in my day, it was much more so than it is now.
Correct.
And one of the greatest compliments that I ever had paid me was paid to me by Lemon on Christmas before he died.
He came down and spent about two hours talking.
And he got up and he put his arm around me.
And of course I'm so short that I came under the pit of his arm.
And he says, you know, said, you are a remarkable person.
I said, well, how do you mean that, Lennon?
He says, just think of the many children's lives that you have touched.
And what an impression that you have left on them to do whatever they did do well.
I said, yes, but you had the leadership of the nation.
You touched everybody's life.
He said, I may have touched everybody's life, but said, you left an imprint
that can never be erased.
I agree.
Well, I taught both of his daughters.
And each time, I would say, Linda, it was hard for her to learn to write and hold her pencil properly.
Because of poor muscle coordination, I thought, and the way that she was taught in the first grade.
I had her in the fourth.
And I said, no, Linda, don't.
Use that finger.
This index finger is the one that has the connection directly to the brain.
It gives you that muscular movement.
Not this one.
Put it down here with this.
And rest it on this finger.
Make that one your wrist and fold it back this way.
And then go on.
And he says, Linda holds her pencil right today.
Well, that's a little thing.
But as he said, I guess I've left my impression on somebody, some trait.
Oh, I know that's true.
Because education has been a great thing to you.
Well, when you come up not being able to go to school, when you're
Old enough, and you have to wait until Margaret and Len and both get old enough to take to school, then you're responsible for them.
And if they didn't want to do what you wanted them to do, they'd double team on you and work you over.
And you'd go ahead and submit to it and say, yeah, we'll do that.
And that's the way.
And I'd finally get home with them in one piece.
Maybe their shirt tail, his shirt tail would be out.
Margaret's sash would be undone, her hair ribbon off.
But I'd get them home.
Right.
Where did y'all go to school?
First year was up at Stonewall.
And how old were you then?
Little schoolhouse where he signed the education bill.
Right.
And, well...
I'm sure I was seven years old.
So you started later.
Mm-hmm.
And how old were they when they started?
Huh.
Lennon was four.
Four.
Margaret was four.
Mm-hmm.
So they began.
But Lennon was always as large as I was.
Uh-huh.
Large.
And Margaret was, too.
I was, I was just broad as I was long, but I never was tall.
Mm-hmm.
Never was tall.
But you certainly did a lot with education in Texas yourself.
When did you decide to be a teacher, Ava?
All my life I wanted to be a teacher.
I first wanted to be a nurse, and I just couldn't float that deal.
And I wanted to be a teacher.
The first time I ever taught school, I stood state examination and got my certificate.
Because they would allow you to do that.
They would allow me to do that back in the 30s.
No, it was the 20s, by the way.
The first school I taught was 1926.
Where was that?
Right here at Johnson City.
In the Johnson City School itself?
In the Johnson City School.
I taught the 6th and 7th grade.
What did you teach?
I taught all of it, two grades.
I had all the subjects, math and history and geography and English and civics and physiology, as we called it then, and spelling and writing and reading.
And I can tell you one thing.
I drilled on mathematics, reading, writing, and arithmetic.
and the other came secondary.
With two classes, it was hard to do.
And you had 40 students in your room.
It didn't come easy.
I had Lennon's baby sister in the sixth grade, Lucia.
Wow.
So you were how old teaching the sixth grade then?
I guess I was 18.
About 18 years old.
About 18 years old.
How long did you do that?
Well, I taught that year and I taught the next year.
Let's see.
Corky was born in 29.
I didn't teach 29.
I didn't teach 30.
But I did teach in 32 and 33.
Then on.
Didn't know, and I'll take it back.
I started to work.
I never did get for $70 a month.
Most never did get.
I started out $40 a month.
Up here at Johnson City.
And then I got a $70 a month school up at Rocky Creek, which is out of town.
And I drove up there.
And then I finished out
In 33, I finished out the school at Stonewall, up there, the little junction school.
And I drove up there.
I finished that one out for Stella Luxton.
And Mr. Klein, that has been working for them for 20 years, was one of my students.
Really?
That's right, and his wife was one of my students.
And it's just, when I go up there, I can't, I look at them, I was quite a young person, still, and they were big boys going to school.
Great big boys.
It's not too much difference, I guess maybe eight or nine years in our ages.
But you were still their teacher.
I was still their teacher, and they respected me.
They were kind.
Yeah.
You went on then to get the education?
I didn't.
Because I have talked to you about this before.
I decided that working, then I went to work for the PEC.
And I worked for them as chief accounting clerk for five years.
And we had 17 counties to bail out.
And Ida Mae Prane was cashier.
And I was the bookkeeper.
Mm-hmm.
clerk, and we worked all the connects, disconnects.
We took care of all the customers' readings and posting and everything, of all of the work, just she and I.
The Pernell's Electric Cooperative was new.
That we have right up here, was new then.
And I started out right then.
And then in 48, I
decided that I was going back to college.
And I went in the summertime of 48 to check in to see how many college credit hours that I had left when I went.
And at that time, it was called a summer normal, and we had two-hour courses.
And they changed it to three-hour courses.
Well, I started out with 12 flat hours.
And I took courses that summer.
And if I could make a B average, I could take an extra course.
Well, I made my B average, I'll guarantee you.
And then that winter, I took correspondence courses and went to school.
And that was winter of 48 and the first of 49.
And then I went back to summer school, and I still had my B average.
I took 15 hours of summer school.
Went back, and in 1950, I walked down the aisle with my BA degree.
Right.
That's so right.
At San Marcos?
At Trinity University.
At Trinity University.
In the afternoons, I taught first grade.
And the bus came through here.
My students were all dismissed.
2 o'clock.
And the bus came through here at 2.30.
I boarded that bus and went into San Antonio and went to night school at Trinity University every night.
And came back home.
Now, this you don't do today.
And on Saturday, I took Saturday classes for teachers.
It's in Marcus.
Mm-hmm.
And I carried a full load down there.
And when I tell you a full load, I mean a full college load.
And on Saturday classes, down here.
That's how I got through in 1950.
And you finished that teaching certification?
Yes, sir.
In two years.
That was terrific.
Well, you can bet on that.
People don't do that today.
They don't burn the candle at both ends.
I could read on that bus just as fast as...
I could anywhere else.
I had geared myself to study on the bus and get my lessons and prepare myself and go right on.
And then I said, well, that's as far as I'm going.
And Olin said, no, Ava, you are not stopping now.
I said, but I'm tired.
He says, while you're in the mood of studying and you're
Life is geared to that.
You're going after that master's.
I said, oh, and I just don't want to go back to school anymore.
And he just walked to the door, and he says, you get your books and things ready, because I want you to have a master's degree.
Well, I thought, well, if he is that persistent and really wants me to, that's the least I can do.
So I worked in another year.
And I taught school every day.
I finished my master's.
And that was in special?
Well, I took my master's in education, but curricular guidance.
in education and planning and steering a group.
And I have thought so many times about what I have been through with our national park up here with these people.
I'm head technician and have three people to supervise.
And I couldn't understand.
And when I was in San Antonio, I knew I was lead teacher for social studies for the district.
You know, plan your curriculum for all the entire district.
Let's us all get together, and we'll have a certain goal and a certain plan, and we'll work it all out together.
So if one child is transferred from one school to another, he isn't lost.
We'll all be.
more or less working together.
And I counted up those teachers, I had 65.
But I wasn't qualified to take care of three women here.
Yeah, that's the thing that people don't realize, that the National Park Service in Johnson City itself did more to the detriment of the local population
and less to truly giving Lyndon Johnson his rights as an individual and president.
